      = Laura Secord\n|pages        = {{page needed|date=June 2013}}\n|editor-last  = Zaslow\n|editor-first = Morris\n|title        = The Defended Border; Upper Canada and the War of 1812\n|url          = https://archive.org/details/trent_0116300872201\n|url-access   = registration\n|year         = 1964\n|publisher    = Macmillan Co. of Canada}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n====Journals and magazines====\n\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite journal\n|ref       = harv\n|first     = Philip E. J.\n|last      = Green\n|title     = Billy Green and the Battle of Stoney Creek, June 5\u20136, 1813.\n|url       = http://www.napoleon-series.org/military/Warof1812/2013/Issue20/Green.pdf\n|publisher = International Napoleonic Society\n|journal   = War of 1812 Magazine\n|date=May 2013\n|volume    = 20\n\n}}\n* {{cite journal\n|ref     = harv\n|first   = Cecilia\n|last    = Morgan\n|title   = 'Of Slender Frame and Delicate Appearance': The Placing Of Laura Secord in the Narratives of Canadian Loyalist History\n|url     = http://www.erudit.org/revue/jcha/1994/v5/n1/031079ar.pdf\n|journal = [[Canadian Historical Association|Journal of the Canadian Historical Association]]\n|year    = 1994\n|volume  = 5\n|pages   = 195\u2013212\n|doi     = 10.7202/031079ar}}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n====Newspapers====\n\n{{Refbegin|colwidth=40em}}\n* {{cite news\n|ref        = {{SfnRef|''Acton Free Press'' staff|1901}}\n|author     = ''Acton Free Press'' staff\n|newspaper  = Acton Free Press\n|title      = Monument to Memory of Laura Secord\n|date       = 1901-06-27\n|page       = 3\n|url        = http://news.haltonhills.halinet.on.ca/85691/page/3\n|accessdate = 2012-07-08}}\n* {{cite news\n |ref         = {{SfnRef|Berry|2010}}\n |url         = http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2010/04/13/final-chapter-nears-for-laura-secord\n |title       = Final Chapter Nears for Laura Secord\n |last        = Berry\n |first       = Sylvie\n |newspaper   = [[Niagara Falls Review]]\n |date        = 2010-04-13\n |accessdate  = 2012-10-26\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303230347/http://www.niagarafallsreview.ca/2010/04/13/final-chapter-nears-for-laura-secord\n |archivedate = 3 March 2016\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |ref         = {{SfnRef|Fraser|2013}}\n |last        = Fraser\n |first       = Don\n |title       = Coin and stamp celebrate a Canadian heroine\n |newspaper   = Welland Tribune\n |date        = 2013-06-21\n |url         = http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2013/06/21/coin-and-stamp-celebrate-a-canadian-heroine\n |accessdate  = 2013-09-16\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055906/http://www.wellandtribune.ca/2013/06/21/coin-and-stamp-celebrate-a-canadian-heroine\n |archivedate = 4 March 2016\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n* {{cite news\n|ref        = {{SfnRef|Hunter|2012}}\n|url        = https://www.thestar.com/news/books/article/1203013--laura-secord-heroine-of-the-war-of-1812-column\n|last       = Hunter\n|first      = Jennifer\n|title      = Laura Secord: Heroine of the War of 1812\n|date       = 2012-06-02\n|newspaper  = [[Toronto Star]]\n|accessdate = 2012-07-09}}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n====Web====\n\n{{Refbegin|40em}}\n* {{cite web\n|ref        = harv\n|first      = Kym\n|last       = Bird\n|url        = http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/articles/sarah-anne-curzon\n|title      = Sarah Anne Curzon\n|publisher  = [[Historica Dominion Institute]]\n|year       = 2012\n|accessdate = 2012-07-08}}\n* {{cite web\n|ref        = {{SfnRef|Bradburn|2013}}\n|url        = http://torontoist.com/2013/04/historicist-a-box-of-laura-secord/\n|title      = Historicist: A Box of Laura Secord\n|first      = Jamie\n|last       = Bradburn\n|work       = [[Gothamist|Torontoist]]\n|date       = 2013-04-13\n|accessdate = 2013-05-06}}\n* {{cite web\n|ref        = {{SfnRef|Jonasson|2012}}\n|first      = Linda\n|last       = Jonasson\n|date       = 2012-06-30\n|publisher  = Maranatha News\n|title      = Laura Secord: Housewife Turned Heroine\n|url        = http://www.maranathanews.com/2012/06/30/laura-secord-housewife-turned-heroine/\n|accessdate = 2012-07-09}}\n* {{cite web\n|ref        = harv\n|last       = McKenzie\n|first      = Ruth\n|url        = http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?BioId=38629\n|title      = Laura Secord\n|publisher  = [[University of Toronto]]/[[Laval University]]\n|year       = 2000\n|accessdate = 2012-07-08}}\n* {{cite web\n|ref        = harv\n|title      = Laura Secord: Homespun Heroine\n|publisher  = Historical Narratives of Early Canada\n|url        = http://www.uppercanadahistory.ca/1812/18127.html\n|last       = Wilson\n|first      = W. R.\n|year       = 2010\n|accessdate = 2012-10-16}}\n\n{{Refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* {{cite book|author-link=Sarah Anne Curzon|first=Sarah Anne|last=Curzon|title=Laura Secord, the Heroine of 1812: A Drama and Other Poems|year=2008|origyear=1887|publisher=Echo Library|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XuAHtRM3Z88C&pg=PA1|isbn=978-1-4068-9015-0|location=|pages=}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hemmings|first=David|title=Laura Ingersoll Secord: A Heroine and her Family|year=2010|publisher=Bygones Publishing|isbn=978-0-9865772-1-5|location=|pages=}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hume|first=Blanche|title=Laura Secord|edition=2|location=|pages=|year=1935|isbn=|publisher=[[McGraw-Hill|The Ryerson Press]]|oclc=797044869}}\n* {{cite book|last=Lunn|first=Janet|title=Laura Secord, A Story of Courage|url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_9780887765384|url-access=registration|year=2001|publisher=[[Tundra Books]]|isbn=978-1-77049-384-1|location=|pages=}}\n* {{cite book|last=MacDonald|first=Cheryl|title=Laura Secord: The Heoric Adventures of a Canadian Legend|year=2005|publisher=Altitude Publishing Canada|isbn=978-1-55439-016-8|location=|pages=}}\n* {{cite book|last=Robinson|first=Helen Caister|title=Laura: A Portrait of Laura Secord|year=1981|publisher=[[Dundurn Press]]|isbn=978-0-919670-52-5|location=|pages=}}\n* {{cite journal\n<!-- |ref        = harv -->|last=Tate|first=Marsha Ann|date=|year=2005|title=Looking for Laura Secord on the Web: Using a Famous Figure from the War of 1812 as a Model for Evaluating Historical Web Sites|url=|journal=[[The History Teacher]]|publisher=The Society for History Education|volume=38|issue=2|pages=|via=}}\n\n{{Refend|Last Name=MacDonald|First Name=Cheryl|Title=Laura Secord:The Heroic Adventures of a Canadian Legend|Book=|Year of Pulication=2003|ISBN=1554390168|Pages=110|Series=True Canadian Amazing Stories}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Commons category|Laura Secord}}\n{{Wikisourcecat|Laura Secord}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060319121339/http://www.galafilm.com/1812/e/people/secord_speach.html Laura Secord's message to the Prince of Wales, 1860]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120915055731/https://www.historica-dominion.ca/content/heritage-minutes/laura-secord Laura Secord Heritage Minute video at Historica Dominion]\n* [http://www.canadiana.org/ECO/mtq?doc=06250 \"The Story of Laura Secord\", ''Canadian reminiscences'' by EA Currie (1900)]\n* [http://www.nflibrary.ca/nfplindex/show.asp?id=102660&b=1 Laura Secord monument on Queenston Heights]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080603121141/http://www.niagarapoetry.ca/warcontents.htm Poems about Laura Secord on the Niagara Falls Poetry Project]\n\n{{War of 1812}}\n{{Portal bar|Canada|History}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Secord, Laura}}\n[[Category:1775 births]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:British emigrants to pre-Confederation Ontario]]\n[[Category:Canadian folklore]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of the War of 1812]]\n[[Category:Women in war in Canada]]\n[[Category:People from Great Barrington, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Niagara Falls, Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Niagara-on-the-Lake]]\n[[Category:Persons of National Historic Significance (Canada)]]\n[[Category:Pre-Confederation Ontario people]]\n[[Category:Women in 19th-century warfare]]\n[[Category:Immigrants to Upper Canada]]\n", "name_user": "2001:1970:549c:3e00:9085:caa8:e32c:3119", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eFamily history and early life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_Secord"}
{"title_page": "Dick Donovan", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{for|Dick Donovan, the pseudonym of the British author|J. E. Preston Muddock}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Dick Donovan\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|image=Dick Donovan 1961.jpg\n|caption=Donovan in 1961\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1927|12|7}}\n|birth_place=[[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1997|1|6|1927|12|7}}\n|death_place=[[Weymouth, Massachusetts]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 24\n|debutyear=1950\n|debutteam=Boston Braves\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=June 12\n|finalyear=1965\n|finalteam=Cleveland Indians\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=122\u201399\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=3.67\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=880\n|teams=\n* [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] ({{mlby|1950}}\u2013{{mlby|1952}})\n* [[Detroit Tigers]] ({{mlby|1954}})\n* [[Chicago White Sox]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1960}})\n* [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] ({{mlby|1961}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|1962}}\u2013{{mlby|1965}})\n|highlights=\n* 5\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1955]], [[1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1961]]\u2013[[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1962\u00b2]])\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual ERA leaders|AL ERA leader]] (1961)\n}}\n'''Richard Edward Donovan''' (December 27, 1927 \u2013 January 6, 1997) was an American [[Major League Baseball]] [[pitcher]] who played for the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] (1950\u20131952), [[Detroit Tigers]] (1954), [[Chicago White Sox]] (1955\u20131960), [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] (1961) and [[Cleveland Indians]] (1962\u20131965). He batted left-handed and threw right-handed, stood {{convert|6|ft|3|in}} tall and weighed {{convert|190|lb}}.\n\nA [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]] native, Donovan graduated from [[North Quincy High School]] and served in the [[United States Navy]] during and after [[World War II]]. Signed by the hometown Braves, he reached the major leagues in 1950 but was used sporadically over the next several years. While pitching for the minor league [[Atlanta Crackers]], he learned how to throw a [[Slider (baseball)|slider]], and this helped him claim a spot in the White Sox' rotation in 1955. He was an [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] in his first major league season, winning 15 games with only nine losses. In 1956, he led the [[American League]] (AL) with a 1.155 [[walks plus hits per innings pitched]]. He led the AL with a .727 [[winning percentage]] in 1957, going 16\u20136, and he won 15 games for the White Sox in 1958. He pitched in the [[1959 World Series]] against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], losing Game 3 but earning the [[Save (baseball)|save]] in Game 5. Donovan struggled in 1960 and was moved to the [[bullpen]], then got selected in the [[1960 Major League Baseball expansion draft|expansion draft]] by the Senators after the season. He had his best year with the new club in 1961, leading the AL with a 2.40 [[earned run average]] (ERA), though his won-loss record was just 10\u201310. Traded to the Indians for [[Jimmy Piersall]] after the season, he won 20 games his first year with Cleveland. Donovan pitched three more years for the Indians after that before getting released midway through 1965. Following his baseball career, he sold insurance and held other jobs in the [[Quincy, Massachusetts]] area before dying of cancer in 1997.\n\nDonovan was unusually good at hitting for a pitcher, homering 15 times in his big-league career.\n\n==Early life==\nDonovan was the youngest of five children of Jeremiah and Gertrude Donovan. He grew up in Boston and attended [[North Quincy High School]], where he played [[shortstop]] until his senior year, when he switched positions and became a [[pitcher]]. Donovan also pitched for the [[Catholic Youth Organization]]. [[Ken Coleman]], broadcaster for the [[Cleveland Indians]], told the story that once, Donovan was invited to pitch for the [[American Legion]] All-Star team in an [[exhibition game]]. Upon arriving at the park, he was told that he would merely be used in the [[bullpen]]. Protesting that he had been promised more, Donovan left the field and went home. \"To me, this incident typified the makeup of Dick. He still has the determination to do what he thinks is right, and has the wonderful ability to see the humor in a situation,\" Coleman said.<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web|last=Wancho|first=Joseph|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/af5aebda|title=Dick Donovan|work=SABR|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Donovan's pitching attracted the attention of [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]]' scout Jeff Jones, who signed him after his senior year and proclaimed him \"the fire-ballingest pitcher\u201d he had seen since spotting [[Bob Feller]] pitching in high school. Donovan graduated during [[World War II]], though, and he served three years in the [[United States Navy]] before beginning his professional career in 1947.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Early years===\nDonovan's career started far south of his home, with the [[Fort Lauderdale Braves]] of the [[Class C (baseball)|Class C]] [[Florida International League]]. He had a 7\u201315 [[Win-loss record (pitching)|record]] and a 4.17 [[earned run average]] (ERA) in his first professional season but still got promoted to the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Evansville Braves]] of the [[Illinois-Indiana-Iowa League]]. With Evansville in 1948, he had a 12\u20139 record and a 3.08 ERA.<ref name=\"minors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=donova001ric|title=Dick Donovan Minor Leagues Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He moved on to the [[Hartford Chiefs]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] in 1949, posting a 12\u20136 record and a 2.66 ERA and earning a promotion to the [[Class AAA (baseball)|Class AAA]] [[Milwaukee Brewers (American Association)|Milwaukee Brewers]] of the [[American Association (20th Century)|American Association]], the Braves' top farm team, for a couple games.<ref name=\"minors\"/> \n\nBy 1950, Donovan was one of three rookie pitching prospects looking to make it with the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]], along with [[Norman Roy]] and George Uhle, Jr. The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' wrote, \"The best of the prospects seems to be Roy, who had a great year in 1949 at Milwaukee.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Vince|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19500103&id=m9gNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1483,634622&hl=en|title=Once Over Lightly|work=The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=January 3, 1950|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Uhle apparently got hurt (he only appeared in four games in the minors that year and never pitched again), but Roy and Donovan both made the Braves out of [[spring training]], Donovan as a starter.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=royno01&t=p&year=1950|title=Normie Roy 1950 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He made his major league debut on April 24, giving up six [[Run (baseball)|runs]] (five earned) in {{frac|6|2|3}} [[Innings pitched|innings]] and taking the loss in a 6\u20134 defeat to the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BSN/BSN195004240.shtml|title=Brooklyn Dodgers at Boston Braves Box Score, April 24, 1950|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Donovan lost his next start, moved to the bullpen, then went to Milwaukee after appearing in two more games.<ref name=\"1950 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1950|title=Dick Donovan 1950 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He was called up in June and in September but spent most of the rest of the year in the minors.<ref name=\"1950 Donovan\"/> In 10 games (three starts) his rookie year, Donovan had an 0\u20132 record, an 8.19 ERA, nine [[strikeout]]s, and 34 [[Walk (baseball)|walks]] in {{frac|29|2|3}} innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/> His numbers were not much better at Milwaukee, where in 19 games (10 starts) he had a 3\u20136 record, a 6.24 ERA, 44 strikeouts, and 33 walks in 75 innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nIn 1951, Donovan started the season with the Braves again but was again moved to the bullpen after two starts.<ref name=\"1951 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=donova001ric|title=Dick Donovan 1951 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He had a 5.27 ERA (with no record) in eight games with the Braves and did not appear for them after June 5.<ref name=\"1951 Donovan\"/> Spending most of the season with Milwaukee, Donovan had more success with the Brewers in 1951. He had a 7\u20135 record, a 3.28 ERA, 88 strikeouts, and 59 walks in 129 innings, and he helped the Brewers win the American Association pennant.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"minors\"/> However, he did not pitch for the Braves in September.<ref name=\"1951 Donovan\"/>\n\nSimilarly to his previous two years, Donovan started the season with the Braves, then spent most of the year in Milwaukee, with the exception of a brief call-up in late May to early June. In his only two starts, he gave up six runs in one and was pulled from the game in the other after walking the first three hitters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1952|title=Dick Donovan 1952 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He had a 5.54 ERA and an 0\u20132 record with the Braves. With Milwaukee, he appeared in 16 games (12 starts), posting a 4\u20136 record, a 4.55 ERA, 36 strikeouts, and 43 walks in 91 innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nDonovan hoped to remain in Milwaukee for the 1953 season, because the Braves moved there from Boston. However, he failed to make the team out of spring training this time, and the Braves tried to send him to their new AAA affiliate, the [[Toledo Mud Hens]]. Fearing he would remain in the minor leagues, Donovan requested a trade. \u201cI believed I could win in the major leagues and wanted a chance to prove it,\" he said.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> [[John Quinn (baseball executive)|John Quinn]] denied his request at first, then made him available, but he rejected all deals other teams tried to make for Donovan. Finally, [[Gene Mauch]], Donovan's former roommate and manager of the Braves' [[Class AA (baseball)|Class AA]] affiliate, convinced Donovan to come play for the [[Atlanta Crackers]] of the [[Southern Association]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n\"That was the best thing that ever happened to me,\u201d Donovan said of getting sent to Atlanta. \u201cIt brought me under the wing of [[Whitlow Wyatt|[Whitlow] Wyatt]].\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> A former pitcher for the Dodgers, Wyatt taught Donovan how to throw a [[Slider (baseball)|slider]] while the [[Prospect (sports)|prospect]] was at Atlanta.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Donovan appeared in 32 games (19 starts) for Atlanta, posting an 11\u20138 record, a 3.71 ERA, 132 strikeouts, and 51 walks in 182 innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/> He got his wish after the season, when the Braves sold his contract to the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref name=\"reference\"/> Donovan made the Tigers out of spring training but only appeared in two games before Detroit returned him to the Braves on May 13.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He was happy to accept another assignment to Atlanta, where Wyatt was now the manager.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He responded with his best minor league season yet. In 27 games (all starts) for Atlanta, he had an 18\u20138 record and a 2.69 ERA for the team. Donovan also managed to hit well for the Crackers, slugging 12 [[home run]]s and having 32 [[runs batted in]]. The Crackers won the Southern Association pennant, and Donovan was named their Most Valuable Player.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref>{{Cite web|last=Skelton|first=David E. |url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/9a7e6a05 |title=Pete Burnside|work=SABR|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> After the minor league season, the [[Chicago White Sox]] purchased his contract from Milwaukee.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Chicago White Sox===\n[[File:Dick Donovan 1955.png|thumb|left|150px|Donovan in 1955]]\nDonovan made the White Sox out of spring training in 1955, as a reliever.<ref name=\"1955 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1955|title=Dick Donovan 1955 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> However, he was quickly added to the rotation after [[Bob Keegan]], an [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] who had won 16 games with the White Sox the year before, developed a bone spur on his heel.<ref name=\"slider\">{{cite web|last=Terrell|first=Roy|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1955/06/27/no-longer-a-team-to-be-ignored-the-white-sox-loom-large-in-the-american-league-race-with-speed-defense-and-some-great-pitching|title=No Longer a Team to Be Ignored, the White Sox Loom Large in the American League Race with Speed, Defense and Some Great Pitching|work=Sports Illustrated|date=June 27, 1955|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He finally got his first career win on April 29, in a four-hit [[Shutout (baseball)|shutout]] of the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195504290.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at Chicago White Sox Box Score, April 29, 1955|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> At the plate, he hit his first career home run July 3 against [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Bob Lemon]] in a 14\u20139 loss to the [[Cleveland Indians]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE195507030.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Cleveland Indians Box Score, July 3, 1955|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> With a 10\u20132 record at the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star break]], Donovan returned to Milwaukee as a member of the [[American League]] (AL) All-Star Team, though he did not pitch in the game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"1955 Donovan\"/> His record was 13\u20132 on July 20; Donovan lost his next two starts in July, then suffered appendicitis and missed a month recovering.<ref name=\"1955 Donovan\"/><ref name=\"SABR\"/> He won his first start back on August 21, then went on a five-game losing streak, posting an 8.07 ERA over that span.<ref name=\"1955 Donovan\"/> In his final start of the year, September 24, he threw a five-hit shutout against the [[Kansas City Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195509240.shtml|title=Kansas City Athletics at Chicago White Sox Box Score, September 24, 1955|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Donovan finished his first full season in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) with a 15\u20139 record, a 3.32 ERA, five shutouts, 88 strikeouts, and 48 walks in 187 innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIn his first start of the 1956 season April 20, Donovan gave up three runs in {{frac|7|2|3}} innings and contributed a two-run home run against [[Lou Kretlow]] of Kansas City; he got a no-decision, but the White Sox won 5\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/KC1/KC1195604200.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Kansas City Athletics Box Score, April 20, 1956|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Wins were few and far between for Donovan, who finished July with a 4\u20137 record and a 5.02 ERA. A six-game winning streak and a 2.01 ERA in the last two months improved his numbers by season's end.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1956|title=Dick Donovan 1956 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> When he faced Kansas City on August 15, he limited the Athletics to two hits in a 10\u20130 shutout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/KC1/KC1195608150.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Kansas City Athletics Box Score, August 15, 1956|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Against Cleveland on August 31, he matched zeroes on the scoreboard with Hall of Famer [[Early Wynn]] for nine innings, then won the game in the 10th when his RBI [[Single (baseball)|single]] against Wynn gave the White Sox a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195608312.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Chicago White Sox Box Score, August 31, 1956|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In 34 games (31 starts), he had a 12\u201310 record, a 3.64 ERA, three shutouts, 120 strikeouts, and 59 walks in {{frac|234|2|3}} innings. He led the league with a 1.155 [[walks plus hits per inning pitched]] (WHIP).<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nDonovan threw a shutout against Cleveland on May 25, 1957, allowing a second-inning [[Double (baseball)|double]] to [[Eddie Robinson (baseball)|Eddie Robinson]] that was the only hit for the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE195705250.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Cleveland Indians Box Score, May 25, 1957|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He relinquished four runs in his next start against Cleveland on May 30 but had three hits and drove in three runs in a 6\u20134 victory over the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195705301.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Chicago White Sox Box Score, May 30, 1957|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On July 20, Donovan threw another one-hit shutout in a game against the Red Sox, with [[Ted Williams]]'s fourth-inning single being the only hit for Boston.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195707200.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at Chicago White Sox Box Score, July 20, 1957|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Possessing an eight and three record on July 3, he won seven games in a row, a streak that did not end until August 29, in an 11-inning, 2\u20131 loss to the Yankees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1957}|title=Dick Donovan 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Donovan, as a member of the White Sox, led the {{mlby|1957}} AL in [[winning percentage]], posting a 16\u20136 record for a .727 winning percentage. He also led the league with 16 [[complete game]]s and struck out 88 in {{frac|220|2|3}} innings. Donovan finished 13th in AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player (MVP) Award]] voting and came in second to the [[National League]]'s [[Warren Spahn]] in [[Cy Young Award]] voting, in an era where the Cy Young was only presented to one pitcher for both leagues.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIt looked like Donovan would have the opposite winning percentage in 1958, after he got off to a 3\u201310 start with an ERA of 4.29.<ref name=\"1958 splits\"/> In the midst of the 3\u201310 start, on June 15, he shut out the [[Baltimore Orioles]] in the second game of a [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BAL/BAL195806152.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Baltimore Orioles Box Score, June 15, 1958|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The second half of the season was different, as Donovan won 12 of 16 decisions and posted a 2.01 ERA.<ref name=\"1958 splits\">{{cite web|author=SI Staff|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1959/04/13/chicago-white-sox|title=Chicago White Sox|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 13, 1959|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> On August 3, he held the Yankees to one run and singled home a run off of [[Whitey Ford]] in a 3-1 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195808031.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Chicago White Sox Box Score, August 3, 1958|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He threw back-to-back shutouts against the Tigers August 29 and September 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1958|title=Dick Donovan 1958 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In 34 starts, Donovan had a 15\u201314 record, a 3.01 ERA, four shutouts, 127 strikeouts, and 58 walks in 248 innings. He had the lowest [[walks per nine innings]] (1.9) of all AL pitchers and finished 25th in MVP voting.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nDonovan was part of the \"Go-Go Sox\" team that won Chicago's first AL pennant since [[1919 Chicago White Sox season|1919]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> After winning his first start in 1959, he went six weeks without winning a game. \"There's been nothing wrong with my stride or rhythm,\" said Donovan. \"I just seem more prone to lapses in concentration this year.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Woodcock|first=Les|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1959/06/01/baseballs-week|title=Baseball's Week|work=Sports Illustrated|date=June 1, 1959|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> May 12, he hit a two-run home run against [[Ike Delock]] but took a no-decision after running into trouble in the seventh inning; however, the White Sox beat Boston 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BOS/BOS195905120.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Boston Red Sox Box Score, May 12, 1959|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> A sore shoulder kept him out between July 21 and August 16.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"1959 Donovan\"/> In late-August, the White Sox faced Cleveland, a competitive team that trailed them by 1.5 games in the standings, for a four-game series.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Donovan took the opportunity to throw his lone shutout of the year, defeating them 2\u20130 on August 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE195908290.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Cleveland Indians Box Score, August 29, 1959|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The White Sox took a 5.5 game lead after sweeping the Indians, and 10,000 appreciative fans showed up to welcome them back to [[Midway International Airport]] when they returned to Chicago.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Donovan was 9\u20136 on September 2 but lost his last four decisions to finish 9\u201310.<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"1959 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1959|title=Dick Donovan 1959 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He appeared in 31 games (29 starts) for the White Sox, posting a 3.66 ERA and striking out 71 in {{frac|179|2|3}} innings pitched.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nThe White Sox faced the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] in the [[1959 World Series]]. Donovan got the start in Game 3 and held the Dodgers to one baserunner through the first six innings. After getting two outs in the seventh, though, he walked [[Norm Larker]] and [[Gil Hodges]] on nine pitches, prompting manager [[Al L\u00f3pez]] to replace him on the mound with [[Gerry Staley]]. Staley gave up a [[Single (baseball)|single]] to pinch-hitter [[Carl Furillo]], allowing two runs to score, and Donovan took the loss in the 3\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{cite web|last=Abrams|first=Al|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19591005&id=A8lRAAAAIBAJ&pg=3538,543793&hl=en|title=Sidelights on Sports|work=The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=October 5, 1959|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In Game 5, Donovan was called on in the eighth inning with one out after the Dodgers had loaded the bases, with the White Sox clinging to a 1\u20130 lead. He got Furillo to hit into a [[pop fly]], then got [[Don Zimmer]] to [[Fly ball|fly out]] to left field before pitching a scoreless ninth to earn the [[Save (baseball)|save]] for the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAN/LAN195910060.shtml|title=1959 World Series Game 5, White Sox at Dodgers, October 6|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Donovan was also used in Game 6, but he gave up three runs (including a home run to [[Willy Moon]]) without recording an out as the White Sox lost the game 9\u20133 and the Dodgers won the World Series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195910080.shtml|title=1959 World Series Game 6, Dodgers at White Sox, October 8|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring spring training in 1960, the [[Associated Press]] reported a rumor that the White Sox were looking to trade Donovan and [[Earl Battey]] to the Tigers for [[Paul Foytack]].<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=897&dat=19600317&id=_ExPAAAAIBAJ&pg=2983,3248491&hl=en|title=More Talk of Sievers Trade Is Expected|work=Prescott Evening Courier|date=March 17, 1960|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Nothing came of it, and Foytack had a bad year for the Tigers, going 2-11 with a 6.14 ERA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/f/foytapa01.shtml|title=Paul Foytack Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> However, Donovan did not fare much better with the White Sox, perhaps due to a sore arm.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He posted a 6.75 ERA in his first 10 games (seven starts), never making it past the seventh inning.<ref name=\"1960 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1960|title=Dick Donovan 1960 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> After only going {{frac|2|2|3}} innings in a no-decision (eventual loss) against Detroit on June 2, Donovan was removed from the rotation in favor of [[Russ Kemmerer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/tgl.cgi?team=CHW&t=p&year=1960|title=1960 Chicago White Sox Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> He made just one more start for the club all year, a July 29 game against the Senators in which he relinquished three runs in {{frac|3|1|3}} innings in an eventual 7\u20135 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS1/WS1196007290.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Washington Senators Box Score, July 29, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> His ERA improved somewhat in the bullpen, but it was still 5.38, the highest it had been in any of Donovan's full major league seasons. This was not reflected in his won-loss record, as he finished the season with a 6\u20131 mark.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Still, the White Sox left him unprotected from the [[1960 Major League Baseball expansion draft|expansion draft]] after the season, and Donovan became an original member of the new [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] franchise.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Washington Senators===\n''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' did not expect much from Donovan entering the year; their preview of the first-year Senators stated, \"In two seasons, 1957\u201358, Dick Donovan won 31 games for the White Sox. Perhaps he will remember how he did it.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=SI Staff|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1961/04/10/washington-senators|title=Washington Senators|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 10, 1961|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Donovan started the first game in the expansion Senators' history, against his old team, the White Sox. He had a 3\u20132 lead through the sixth inning, but errors by [[Gene Woodling]] and [[Dale Long]] allowed a couple unearned runs to score, and the Senators lost 4\u20133. After the game, someone wished Donovan better luck next time; the angry pitcher nearly spit out of rage.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bingham|first=Walter|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1961/04/24/a-change-after-60-years|title=A Change after 60 Years|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 24, 1961|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Donovan would often be a tough-luck loser that season, losing his first five decisions of the season by one run, including 1\u20130 loss to Minnesota on April 23.<ref name=\"Piersall Traded\">{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=19611005&id=oAMuAAAAIBAJ&pg=2495,3719307&hl=en|title=Piersall Traded for Dick Donovan|work=Rome News-Tribune|date=October 5, 1961|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Bad Luck\">{{cite web|last=Hackleman|first=Jim|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1979&dat=19620524&id=45YiAAAAIBAJ&pg=774,3782825|title=Bad-Luck Donovan 8-Game Winner This Time|work=The Sumter Daily Item|date=May 24, 1962|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"1961 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1961|title=Dick Donovan 1961 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> He did not win a game until June 2, against Kansas City.<ref name=\"1961 Donovan\"/> For his second victory, Donovan threw a shutout in the first game of a June 9 doubleheader against his old team the White Sox, but it took the Senators 10 innings to get him a run to give him the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS2/WS2196106091.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Washington Senators Box Score, June 9, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Through June 30, he was 3\u20138, but he went 7\u20132 the rest of the way.<ref name=\"1961 Donovan\"/> Despite his losing record, he was the Senators' lone representative at both of the year's All-Star Games, pitching two scoreless innings in the first one at [[Candlestick Park]]. \"Donovan is a real professional,\u201d Senators' manager [[Mickey Vernon]] said. \u201cHe knows how to pitch and gives you an all-out effort. Dick just doesn\u2019t throw the ball -- he has every pitch planned.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His record was just 10\u201310 at season's end, but his pitching was the best of his career, as his 2.40 ERA (a career-low) led the American League. In {{frac|168|2|3}} innings, he gave up only 138 hits, leading the AL with a 1.026 WHIP. He finished 17th in MVP voting.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Shortly after the season, on October 5, the Senators traded him, [[Gene Green (baseball)|Gene Green]], and [[Jim Mahoney]] to the [[Cleveland Indians]] for [[Jimmy Piersall]].<ref name=\"reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/donovdi01.shtml|title=Dick Donovan Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Indians===\nWith the Indians in 1962, Donovan had better luck.<ref name=\"Bad Luck\"/> Used as the Indians' [[Opening Day]] starter, he shut out the Red Sox on April 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BOS/BOS196204100.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Boston Red Sox Box Score, April 10, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In fact, he did not allow a run until his third game of the year, starting the season with 19 scoreless innings.<ref name=\"1962 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1962|title=Dick Donovan 1962 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He commenced with an 8\u20130 start, becoming the first pitcher in the major leagues to eight wins on May 24.<ref name=\"Bad Luck\"/> Donovan was selected to the AL All-Star team in both games, allowing a run over two innings in the first one and not pitching in the second one.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Twice during the year, he hit two home runs in a game\u2014May 18 against Detroit and August 31 against Baltimore; the Indians won both instances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=b&year=1962|title=Dick Donovan 1962 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He limited the Orioles to two hits July 2 in a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196207020.shtml|title=Baltimore Orioles at Cleveland Indians Box Score, July 2, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> On August 26, he limited Boston to two hits in a 4\u20130 victory; the shutout was his third of the year against the Red Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196208262.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at Cleveland Indians Box Score, August 26, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> During a game on September 4, he limited the White Sox to two runs through 12 innings but took the loss after giving up a run in the 13th.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA196209040.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Chicago White Sox Box Score, September 4, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Donovan was rewarded for his performance in 1962, when he won 20 games for the first time in his career. In 34 starts, he had 16 complete games and five shutouts (most in the AL) in 250<small>{{fraction|1|3}}</small> innings pitched, all of them new career-highs, for Cleveland. His ERA was 3.59.<ref name=\"reference\"/> After the season, he finished fifth in MVP voting, and the ''[[Sporting News]]'' named him its AL Pitcher of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|author=United Press International|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=19621121&id=D_YvAAAAIBAJ&pg=5262,2474618&hl=en|title=Yankees' Mickey Mantle Named 'Most Valuable'|work=The Rome News-Tribune|date=November 21, 1962|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The Indians named him their Man of the Year and gave him a $40,000 contract for 1963.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nDespite his success in 1962, Donovan was the Indians' third starter for 1963, behind [[Mudcat Grant]] and [[Sam McDowell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/tgl.cgi?team=CLE&t=p&year=1963|title=1963 Cleveland Indians Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> On July 5, he held the Yankees to one run, had two hits, and scored a run in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196307050.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Cleveland Indians Box Score, July 5, 1963|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Through August 3, he had a 6\u201310 record, but he won his next four starts by pitching four complete games in a row, including back-to-back shutouts August 8 and August 14 (when he held the White Sox scoreless for 11 innings in a 1\u20130 victory).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1963|title=Dick Donovan 1963 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 30 starts, he had an 11\u201313 record, a 4.24 ERA, three shutouts, 84 strikeouts, and 28 walks in 206 innings. For the second year in a row, he led the league in walks per nine innings, with a 1.2 mark.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nDonovan held the [[Los Angeles Angels]] to two runs over eight innings and drove in a couple of his own with a single against [[Ken McBride]] in a 3\u20132 victory over the Angels on April 23, 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAA/LAA196404230.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Los Angeles Angels Box Score, April 23, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Through August 8, though his record was close to .500 at 6\u20137, his ERA was 4.72. After that, he was removed from the rotation. Though he made four more starts for the Indians that season, they were all in doubleheaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1964|title=Dick Donovan 1964 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Against the White Sox in the second game of a doubleheader during September 6, he relinquished 16 hits but lasted into the 13th inning, when [[Pete Ward]] finally drove in a run to give Chicago a 3\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA196409062.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Chicago White Sox Box Score, September 6, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 30 games (just 23 starts), he had a 7\u20139 record, a 4.55 ERA, no shutouts, 83 strikeouts, and 29 walks in {{frac|158|1|3}} innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIn 1965, Donovan was again a starter for the Indians, but only for his first two games, after which he was moved to the bullpen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1965|title=Dick Donovan 1965 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He had not made it through the sixth inning in either of his starts, and the Indians wanted to give more starts to prospects like [[Sonny Siebert]] and [[Luis Tiant]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Used all but once in relief after that, he was released June 15 after posting a 5.96 ERA in 12 games.<ref name=\"reference\"/>  \u201cI figure baseball was good to me,\u201d Donovan said. \u201cI was good to a lot of people in baseball too -- the hitters. It will be nice to take it easy if I don\u2019t go with another club.\u201d<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nDuring a 15-year major league career, Donovan compiled 122 wins, 880 strikeouts, and a 3.67 ERA, with 101 complete games, 25 shutouts and five saves. In 2,017<small>{{fraction|1|3}}</small> innings pitched, he allowed 1,988 hits and 495 walks.<ref name=\"reference\"/> \n\n==Playing style==\nDonovan threw three pitches: a [[fastball]], a [[curveball]], and a slider. He learned the slider while pitching for Atlanta, when coach and later manager Whitlow Wyatt helped teach it to him.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 1955, when he finally stuck in a major league team's rotation, ''Sports Illustrated'' called it \"one of the most effective pitches in baseball.\"<ref name=\"slider\"/> Among pitchers, Donovan was also an unusually gifted hitter. In 1954, he was the team MVP for Atlanta after hitting 12 home runs and driving in 38 runs in only 27 games.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> With the White Sox, he was frequently used as a pinch-hitter. At the plate in his 15-year major league career, Donovan posted a .163 batting average (113-for-694) with 67 runs, 15 home runs, 64 RBI, and 64 walks.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn February 7, 1959, Donovan married Patricia Casey, a [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]], Massachusetts, resident who was a stewardess for [[United Airlines]]. The couple had two children, Peter and Amy. His friend Wyatt gave him the idea to sell insurance, and Donovan had a home business selling insurance during his MLB career. In 1963, he earned his stockbroker's license and joined the Boston-based firm Eastman & Dillon. After his baseball career, he served as the executive vice president for [[Bache & Co.]]. In 1980, he opened a real estate appraisal office in Quincy, which he ran until 1994. Additionally, Donovan served as distributor with Earth Care Products, a Quincy company that makes products out of recycled plastic. He died from cancer on January 6, 1997.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Major League Baseball all-time leaders in home runs by pitchers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060502001352/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/baseballlibrary/ballplayers/D/Donovan_Dick.stm Baseball Library]\n{{baseballstats|br=d/donovdi01}}\n*{{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{AL ERA champions}}\n{{Sporting News AL Pitcher of the Year Award}}\n{{Cleveland Indians Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{Texas Rangers Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donovan, Dick}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League ERA champions]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Crackers players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Boston Braves players]]\n[[Category:Chicago White Sox players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Fort Lauderdale Braves players]]\n[[Category:Evansville Braves players]]\n[[Category:Hartford Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Milwaukee Brewers (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:North Quincy High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Boston]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1961\u20131971) players]]\n\n\n{{US-baseball-pitcher-1920s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{for|Dick Donovan, the pseudonym of the British author|J. E. Preston Muddock}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n|name=Dick Donovan\n|position=[[Pitcher]]\n|image=Dick Donovan 1961.jpg\n|caption=Donovan in 1961\n|bats=Left\n|throws=Right\n|birth_date={{Birth date|1927|12|7}}\n|birth_place=[[Boston, Massachusetts]]\n|death_date={{death date and age|1997|1|6|1927|12|7}}\n|death_place=[[Weymouth, Massachusetts]]\n|debutleague = MLB\n|debutdate=April 24\n|debutyear=1950\n|debutteam=Boston Braves\n|finalleague = MLB\n|finaldate=June 12\n|finalyear=1965\n|finalteam=Cleveland Indians\n|statleague = MLB\n|stat1label=[[Win\u2013loss record (pitching)|Win\u2013loss record]]\n|stat1value=122\u201399\n|stat2label=[[Earned run average]]\n|stat2value=3.67\n|stat3label=[[Strikeout]]s\n|stat3value=880\n|teams=\n* [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] ({{mlby|1950}}\u2013{{mlby|1952}})\n* [[Detroit Tigers]] ({{mlby|1954}})\n* [[Chicago White Sox]] ({{mlby|1955}}\u2013{{mlby|1960}})\n* [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] ({{mlby|1961}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|1962}}\u2013{{mlby|1965}})\n|highlights=\n* 5\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[1955 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|1955]], [[1961 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (first game)|1961]]\u2013[[1962 Major League Baseball All-Star Game (second game)|1962\u00b2]])\n* [[List of Major League Baseball annual ERA leaders|AL ERA leader]] (1961)\n}}\n'''Richard Edward Donovan''' (December 27, 1927 \u2013 January 6, 1997) was an American [[Major League Baseball]] [[pitcher]] who played for the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]] (1950\u20131952), [[Detroit Tigers]] (1954), [[Chicago White Sox]] (1955\u20131960), [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] (1961) and [[Cleveland Indians]] (1962\u20131965). He batted left-handed and threw right-handed, stood {{convert|6|ft|3|in}} tall and weighed {{convert|190|lb}}.\n\nA [[Boston, Massachusetts|Boston]] native, Donovan graduated from [[North Quincy High School]] and served in the [[United States Navy]] during and after [[World War II]]. Signed by the hometown Braves, he reached the major leagues in 1950 but was used sporadically over the next several years. While pitching for the minor league [[Atlanta Crackers]], he learned how to throw a [[Slider (baseball)|slider]], and this helped him claim a spot in the White Sox' rotation in 1955. He was an [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] in his first major league season, winning 15 games with only nine losses. In 1956, he led the [[American League]] (AL) with a 1.155 [[walks plus hits per innings pitched]]. He led the AL with a .727 [[winning percentage]] in 1957, going 16\u20136, and he won 15 games for the White Sox in 1958. He pitched in the [[1959 World Series]] against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], losing Game 3 but earning the [[Save (baseball)|save]] in Game 5. Donovan struggled in 1960 and was moved to the [[bullpen]], then got selected in the [[1960 Major League Baseball expansion draft|expansion draft]] by the Senators after the season. He had his best year with the new club in 1961, leading the AL with a 2.40 [[earned run average]] (ERA), though his won-loss record was just 10\u201310. Traded to the Indians for [[Jimmy Piersall]] after the season, he won 20 games his first year with Cleveland. Donovan pitched three more years for the Indians after that before getting released midway through 1965. Following his baseball career, he sold insurance and held other jobs in the [[Quincy, Massachusetts]] area before dying of cancer in 1997.\n\nDonovan was unusually good at hitting for a pitcher, homering 15 times in his big-league career.\n\n\n==Early life==\nDonovan was the youngest of five children of Jeremiah and Gertrude Donovan. He grew up in Boston and attended [[North Quincy High School]], where he played [[shortstop]] until his senior year, when he switched positions and became a [[pitcher]]. Donovan also pitched for the [[Catholic Youth Organization]]. [[Ken Coleman]], broadcaster for the [[Cleveland Indians]], told the story that once, Donovan was invited to pitch for the [[American Legion]] All-Star team in an [[exhibition game]]. Upon arriving at the park, he was told that he would merely be used in the [[bullpen]]. Protesting that he had been promised more, Donovan left the field and went home. \"To me, this incident typified the makeup of Dick. He still has the determination to do what he thinks is right, and has the wonderful ability to see the humor in a situation,\" Coleman said.<ref name=\"SABR\">{{cite web|last=Wancho|first=Joseph|url=https://sabr.org/bioproj/person/af5aebda|title=Dick Donovan|work=SABR|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Donovan's pitching attracted the attention of [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]]' scout Jeff Jones, who signed him after his senior year and proclaimed him \"the fire-ballingest pitcher\u201d he had seen since spotting [[Bob Feller]] pitching in high school. Donovan graduated during [[World War II]], though, and he served three years in the [[United States Navy]] before beginning his professional career in 1947.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n==Career==\n===Early years===\nDonovan's career started far south of his home, with the [[Fort Lauderdale Braves]] of the [[Class C (baseball)|Class C]] [[Florida International League]]. He had a 7\u201315 [[Win-loss record (pitching)|record]] and a 4.17 [[earned run average]] (ERA) in his first professional season but still got promoted to the [[Class B (baseball)|Class B]] [[Evansville Braves]] of the [[Illinois-Indiana-Iowa League]]. With Evansville in 1948, he had a 12\u20139 record and a 3.08 ERA.<ref name=\"minors\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=donova001ric|title=Dick Donovan Minor Leagues Statistics & History|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He moved on to the [[Hartford Chiefs]] of the [[Class A (baseball)|Class A]] [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] in 1949, posting a 12\u20136 record and a 2.66 ERA and earning a promotion to the [[Class AAA (baseball)|Class AAA]] [[Milwaukee Brewers (American Association)|Milwaukee Brewers]] of the [[American Association (20th Century)|American Association]], the Braves' top farm team, for a couple games.<ref name=\"minors\"/> \n\nBy 1950, Donovan was one of three rookie pitching prospects looking to make it with the [[Boston Braves (baseball)|Boston Braves]], along with [[Norman Roy]] and George Uhle, Jr. The ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' wrote, \"The best of the prospects seems to be Roy, who had a great year in 1949 at Milwaukee.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Johnson|first=Vince|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19500103&id=m9gNAAAAIBAJ&pg=1483,634622&hl=en|title=Once Over Lightly|work=The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=January 3, 1950|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> Uhle apparently got hurt (he only appeared in four games in the minors that year and never pitched again), but Roy and Donovan both made the Braves out of [[spring training]], Donovan as a starter.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=royno01&t=p&year=1950|title=Normie Roy 1950 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He made his major league debut on April 24, giving up six [[Run (baseball)|runs]] (five earned) in {{frac|6|2|3}} [[Innings pitched|innings]] and taking the loss in a 6\u20134 defeat to the [[Brooklyn Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BSN/BSN195004240.shtml|title=Brooklyn Dodgers at Boston Braves Box Score, April 24, 1950|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Donovan lost his next start, moved to the bullpen, then went to Milwaukee after appearing in two more games.<ref name=\"1950 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1950|title=Dick Donovan 1950 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He was called up in June and in September but spent most of the rest of the year in the minors.<ref name=\"1950 Donovan\"/> In 10 games (three starts) his rookie year, Donovan had an 0\u20132 record, an 8.19 ERA, nine [[strikeout]]s, and 34 [[Walk (baseball)|walks]] in {{frac|29|2|3}} innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/> His numbers were not much better at Milwaukee, where in 19 games (10 starts) he had a 3\u20136 record, a 6.24 ERA, 44 strikeouts, and 33 walks in 75 innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nIn 1951, Donovan started the season with the Braves again but was again moved to the bullpen after two starts.<ref name=\"1951 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/register/player.fcgi?id=donova001ric|title=Dick Donovan 1951 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He had a 5.27 ERA (with no record) in eight games with the Braves and did not appear for them after June 5.<ref name=\"1951 Donovan\"/> Spending most of the season with Milwaukee, Donovan had more success with the Brewers in 1951. He had a 7\u20135 record, a 3.28 ERA, 88 strikeouts, and 59 walks in 129 innings, and he helped the Brewers win the American Association pennant.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"minors\"/> However, he did not pitch for the Braves in September.<ref name=\"1951 Donovan\"/>\n\nSimilarly to his previous two years, Donovan started the season with the Braves, then spent most of the year in Milwaukee, with the exception of a brief call-up in late May to early June. In his only two starts, he gave up six runs in one and was pulled from the game in the other after walking the first three hitters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1952|title=Dick Donovan 1952 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He had a 5.54 ERA and an 0\u20132 record with the Braves. With Milwaukee, he appeared in 16 games (12 starts), posting a 4\u20136 record, a 4.55 ERA, 36 strikeouts, and 43 walks in 91 innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/>\n\nDonovan hoped to remain in Milwaukee for the 1953 season, because the Braves moved there from Boston. However, he failed to make the team out of spring training this time, and the Braves tried to send him to their new AAA affiliate, the [[Toledo Mud Hens]]. Fearing he would remain in the minor leagues, Donovan requested a trade. \u201cI believed I could win in the major leagues and wanted a chance to prove it,\" he said.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> [[John Quinn (baseball executive)|John Quinn]] denied his request at first, then made him available, but he rejected all deals other teams tried to make for Donovan. Finally, [[Gene Mauch]], Donovan's former roommate and manager of the Braves' [[Class AA (baseball)|Class AA]] affiliate, convinced Donovan to come play for the [[Atlanta Crackers]] of the [[Southern Association]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n\"That was the best thing that ever happened to me,\u201d Donovan said of getting sent to Atlanta. \u201cIt brought me under the wing of [[Whitlow Wyatt|[Whitlow] Wyatt]].\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> A former pitcher for the Dodgers, Wyatt taught Donovan how to throw a [[Slider (baseball)|slider]] while the [[Prospect (sports)|prospect]] was at Atlanta.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Donovan appeared in 32 games (19 starts) for Atlanta, posting an 11\u20138 record, a 3.71 ERA, 132 strikeouts, and 51 walks in 182 innings.<ref name=\"minors\"/> He got his wish after the season, when the Braves sold his contract to the [[Detroit Tigers]].<ref name=\"reference\"/> Donovan made the Tigers out of spring training but only appeared in two games before Detroit returned him to the Braves on May 13.<ref name=\"reference\"/> He was happy to accept another assignment to Atlanta, where Wyatt was now the manager.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He responded with his best minor league season yet. In 27 games (all starts) for Atlanta, he had an 18\u20138 record and a 2.69 ERA for the team. Donovan also managed to hit well for the Crackers, slugging 12 [[home run]]s and having 32 [[runs batted in]]. The Crackers won the Southern Association pennant, and Donovan was named their Most Valuable Player.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref>{{Cite web|last=Skelton|first=David E. |url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/9a7e6a05 |title=Pete Burnside|work=SABR|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref> After the minor league season, the [[Chicago White Sox]] purchased his contract from Milwaukee.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Chicago White Sox===\n[[File:Dick Donovan 1955.png|thumb|left|150px|Donovan in 1955]]\nDonovan made the White Sox out of spring training in 1955, as a reliever.<ref name=\"1955 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1955|title=Dick Donovan 1955 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> However, he was quickly added to the rotation after [[Bob Keegan]], an [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] who had won 16 games with the White Sox the year before, developed a bone spur on his heel.<ref name=\"slider\">{{cite web|last=Terrell|first=Roy|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1955/06/27/no-longer-a-team-to-be-ignored-the-white-sox-loom-large-in-the-american-league-race-with-speed-defense-and-some-great-pitching|title=No Longer a Team to Be Ignored, the White Sox Loom Large in the American League Race with Speed, Defense and Some Great Pitching|work=Sports Illustrated|date=June 27, 1955|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> He finally got his first career win on April 29, in a four-hit [[Shutout (baseball)|shutout]] of the [[Boston Red Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195504290.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at Chicago White Sox Box Score, April 29, 1955|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> At the plate, he hit his first career home run July 3 against [[National Baseball Hall of Fame and Museum|Hall of Famer]] [[Bob Lemon]] in a 14\u20139 loss to the [[Cleveland Indians]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE195507030.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Cleveland Indians Box Score, July 3, 1955|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> With a 10\u20132 record at the [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star break]], Donovan returned to Milwaukee as a member of the [[American League]] (AL) All-Star Team, though he did not pitch in the game.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"1955 Donovan\"/> His record was 13\u20132 on July 20; Donovan lost his next two starts in July, then suffered appendicitis and missed a month recovering.<ref name=\"1955 Donovan\"/><ref name=\"SABR\"/> He won his first start back on August 21, then went on a five-game losing streak, posting an 8.07 ERA over that span.<ref name=\"1955 Donovan\"/> In his final start of the year, September 24, he threw a five-hit shutout against the [[Kansas City Athletics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195509240.shtml|title=Kansas City Athletics at Chicago White Sox Box Score, September 24, 1955|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref> Donovan finished his first full season in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB) with a 15\u20139 record, a 3.32 ERA, five shutouts, 88 strikeouts, and 48 walks in 187 innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIn his first start of the 1956 season April 20, Donovan gave up three runs in {{frac|7|2|3}} innings and contributed a two-run home run against [[Lou Kretlow]] of Kansas City; he got a no-decision, but the White Sox won 5\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/KC1/KC1195604200.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Kansas City Athletics Box Score, April 20, 1956|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Wins were few and far between for Donovan, who finished July with a 4\u20137 record and a 5.02 ERA. A six-game winning streak and a 2.01 ERA in the last two months improved his numbers by season's end.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1956|title=Dick Donovan 1956 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> When he faced Kansas City on August 15, he limited the Athletics to two hits in a 10\u20130 shutout.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/KC1/KC1195608150.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Kansas City Athletics Box Score, August 15, 1956|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> Against Cleveland on August 31, he matched zeroes on the scoreboard with Hall of Famer [[Early Wynn]] for nine innings, then won the game in the 10th when his RBI [[Single (baseball)|single]] against Wynn gave the White Sox a 1\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195608312.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Chicago White Sox Box Score, August 31, 1956|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In 34 games (31 starts), he had a 12\u201310 record, a 3.64 ERA, three shutouts, 120 strikeouts, and 59 walks in {{frac|234|2|3}} innings. He led the league with a 1.155 [[walks plus hits per inning pitched]] (WHIP).<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nDonovan threw a shutout against Cleveland on May 25, 1957, allowing a second-inning [[Double (baseball)|double]] to [[Eddie Robinson (baseball)|Eddie Robinson]] that was the only hit for the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE195705250.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Cleveland Indians Box Score, May 25, 1957|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He relinquished four runs in his next start against Cleveland on May 30 but had three hits and drove in three runs in a 6\u20134 victory over the Indians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195705301.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Chicago White Sox Box Score, May 30, 1957|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> On July 20, Donovan threw another one-hit shutout in a game against the Red Sox, with [[Ted Williams]]'s fourth-inning single being the only hit for Boston.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195707200.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at Chicago White Sox Box Score, July 20, 1957|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Possessing an eight and three record on July 3, he won seven games in a row, a streak that did not end until August 29, in an 11-inning, 2\u20131 loss to the Yankees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1957}|title=Dick Donovan 1957 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Donovan, as a member of the White Sox, led the {{mlby|1957}} AL in [[winning percentage]], posting a 16\u20136 record for a .727 winning percentage. He also led the league with 16 [[complete game]]s and struck out 88 in {{frac|220|2|3}} innings. Donovan finished 13th in AL [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player (MVP) Award]] voting and came in second to the [[National League]]'s [[Warren Spahn]] in [[Cy Young Award]] voting, in an era where the Cy Young was only presented to one pitcher for both leagues.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIt looked like Donovan would have the opposite winning percentage in 1958, after he got off to a 3\u201310 start with an ERA of 4.29.<ref name=\"1958 splits\"/> In the midst of the 3\u201310 start, on June 15, he shut out the [[Baltimore Orioles]] in the second game of a [[Doubleheader (baseball)|doubleheader]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BAL/BAL195806152.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Baltimore Orioles Box Score, June 15, 1958|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The second half of the season was different, as Donovan won 12 of 16 decisions and posted a 2.01 ERA.<ref name=\"1958 splits\">{{cite web|author=SI Staff|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1959/04/13/chicago-white-sox|title=Chicago White Sox|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 13, 1959|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> On August 3, he held the Yankees to one run and singled home a run off of [[Whitey Ford]] in a 3-1 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195808031.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Chicago White Sox Box Score, August 3, 1958|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He threw back-to-back shutouts against the Tigers August 29 and September 3.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1958|title=Dick Donovan 1958 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> In 34 starts, Donovan had a 15\u201314 record, a 3.01 ERA, four shutouts, 127 strikeouts, and 58 walks in 248 innings. He had the lowest [[walks per nine innings]] (1.9) of all AL pitchers and finished 25th in MVP voting.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nDonovan was part of the \"Go-Go Sox\" team that won Chicago's first AL pennant since [[1919 Chicago White Sox season|1919]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> After winning his first start in 1959, he went six weeks without winning a game. \"There's been nothing wrong with my stride or rhythm,\" said Donovan. \"I just seem more prone to lapses in concentration this year.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Woodcock|first=Les|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1959/06/01/baseballs-week|title=Baseball's Week|work=Sports Illustrated|date=June 1, 1959|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> May 12, he hit a two-run home run against [[Ike Delock]] but took a no-decision after running into trouble in the seventh inning; however, the White Sox beat Boston 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BOS/BOS195905120.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Boston Red Sox Box Score, May 12, 1959|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> A sore shoulder kept him out between July 21 and August 16.<ref name=\"SABR\"/><ref name=\"1959 Donovan\"/> In late-August, the White Sox faced Cleveland, a competitive team that trailed them by 1.5 games in the standings, for a four-game series.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Donovan took the opportunity to throw his lone shutout of the year, defeating them 2\u20130 on August 29.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE195908290.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Cleveland Indians Box Score, August 29, 1959|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> The White Sox took a 5.5 game lead after sweeping the Indians, and 10,000 appreciative fans showed up to welcome them back to [[Midway International Airport]] when they returned to Chicago.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Donovan was 9\u20136 on September 2 but lost his last four decisions to finish 9\u201310.<ref name=\"reference\"/><ref name=\"1959 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1959|title=Dick Donovan 1959 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref> He appeared in 31 games (29 starts) for the White Sox, posting a 3.66 ERA and striking out 71 in {{frac|179|2|3}} innings pitched.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nThe White Sox faced the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] in the [[1959 World Series]]. Donovan got the start in Game 3 and held the Dodgers to one baserunner through the first six innings. After getting two outs in the seventh, though, he walked [[Norm Larker]] and [[Gil Hodges]] on nine pitches, prompting manager [[Al L\u00f3pez]] to replace him on the mound with [[Gerry Staley]]. Staley gave up a [[Single (baseball)|single]] to pinch-hitter [[Carl Furillo]], allowing two runs to score, and Donovan took the loss in the 3\u20131 defeat.<ref>{{cite web|last=Abrams|first=Al|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&dat=19591005&id=A8lRAAAAIBAJ&pg=3538,543793&hl=en|title=Sidelights on Sports|work=The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=October 5, 1959|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> In Game 5, Donovan was called on in the eighth inning with one out after the Dodgers had loaded the bases, with the White Sox clinging to a 1\u20130 lead. He got Furillo to hit into a [[pop fly]], then got [[Don Zimmer]] to [[Fly ball|fly out]] to left field before pitching a scoreless ninth to earn the [[Save (baseball)|save]] for the White Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAN/LAN195910060.shtml|title=1959 World Series Game 5, White Sox at Dodgers, October 6|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref> Donovan was also used in Game 6, but he gave up three runs (including a home run to [[Willy Moon]]) without recording an out as the White Sox lost the game 9\u20133 and the Dodgers won the World Series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA195910080.shtml|title=1959 World Series Game 6, Dodgers at White Sox, October 8|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring spring training in 1960, the [[Associated Press]] reported a rumor that the White Sox were looking to trade Donovan and [[Earl Battey]] to the Tigers for [[Paul Foytack]].<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=897&dat=19600317&id=_ExPAAAAIBAJ&pg=2983,3248491&hl=en|title=More Talk of Sievers Trade Is Expected|work=Prescott Evening Courier|date=March 17, 1960|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Nothing came of it, and Foytack had a bad year for the Tigers, going 2-11 with a 6.14 ERA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/f/foytapa01.shtml|title=Paul Foytack Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> However, Donovan did not fare much better with the White Sox, perhaps due to a sore arm.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> He posted a 6.75 ERA in his first 10 games (seven starts), never making it past the seventh inning.<ref name=\"1960 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1960|title=Dick Donovan 1960 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> After only going {{frac|2|2|3}} innings in a no-decision (eventual loss) against Detroit on June 2, Donovan was removed from the rotation in favor of [[Russ Kemmerer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/tgl.cgi?team=CHW&t=p&year=1960|title=1960 Chicago White Sox Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> He made just one more start for the club all year, a July 29 game against the Senators in which he relinquished three runs in {{frac|3|1|3}} innings in an eventual 7\u20135 loss.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS1/WS1196007290.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Washington Senators Box Score, July 29, 1960|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> His ERA improved somewhat in the bullpen, but it was still 5.38, the highest it had been in any of Donovan's full major league seasons. This was not reflected in his won-loss record, as he finished the season with a 6\u20131 mark.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Still, the White Sox left him unprotected from the [[1960 Major League Baseball expansion draft|expansion draft]] after the season, and Donovan became an original member of the new [[Washington Senators (1961\u201371)|Washington Senators]] franchise.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n===Washington Senators===\n''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' did not expect much from Donovan entering the year; their preview of the first-year Senators stated, \"In two seasons, 1957\u201358, Dick Donovan won 31 games for the White Sox. Perhaps he will remember how he did it.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=SI Staff|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1961/04/10/washington-senators|title=Washington Senators|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 10, 1961|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Donovan started the first game in the expansion Senators' history, against his old team, the White Sox. He had a 3\u20132 lead through the sixth inning, but errors by [[Gene Woodling]] and [[Dale Long]] allowed a couple unearned runs to score, and the Senators lost 4\u20133. After the game, someone wished Donovan better luck next time; the angry pitcher nearly spit out of rage.<ref>{{cite web|last=Bingham|first=Walter|url=https://vault.si.com/vault/1961/04/24/a-change-after-60-years|title=A Change after 60 Years|work=Sports Illustrated|date=April 24, 1961|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Donovan would often be a tough-luck loser that season, losing his first five decisions of the season by one run, including 1\u20130 loss to Minnesota on April 23.<ref name=\"Piersall Traded\">{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=19611005&id=oAMuAAAAIBAJ&pg=2495,3719307&hl=en|title=Piersall Traded for Dick Donovan|work=Rome News-Tribune|date=October 5, 1961|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Bad Luck\">{{cite web|last=Hackleman|first=Jim|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1979&dat=19620524&id=45YiAAAAIBAJ&pg=774,3782825|title=Bad-Luck Donovan 8-Game Winner This Time|work=The Sumter Daily Item|date=May 24, 1962|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"1961 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1961|title=Dick Donovan 1961 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> He did not win a game until June 2, against Kansas City.<ref name=\"1961 Donovan\"/> For his second victory, Donovan threw a shutout in the first game of a June 9 doubleheader against his old team the White Sox, but it took the Senators 10 innings to get him a run to give him the win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/WS2/WS2196106091.shtml|title=Chicago White Sox at Washington Senators Box Score, June 9, 1961|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Through June 30, he was 3\u20138, but he went 7\u20132 the rest of the way.<ref name=\"1961 Donovan\"/> Despite his losing record, he was the Senators' lone representative at both of the year's All-Star Games, pitching two scoreless innings in the first one at [[Candlestick Park]]. \"Donovan is a real professional,\u201d Senators' manager [[Mickey Vernon]] said. \u201cHe knows how to pitch and gives you an all-out effort. Dick just doesn\u2019t throw the ball -- he has every pitch planned.\"<ref name=\"SABR\"/> His record was just 10\u201310 at season's end, but his pitching was the best of his career, as his 2.40 ERA (a career-low) led the American League. In {{frac|168|2|3}} innings, he gave up only 138 hits, leading the AL with a 1.026 WHIP. He finished 17th in MVP voting.<ref name=\"reference\"/> Shortly after the season, on October 5, the Senators traded him, [[Gene Green (baseball)|Gene Green]], and [[Jim Mahoney]] to the [[Cleveland Indians]] for [[Jimmy Piersall]].<ref name=\"reference\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/d/donovdi01.shtml|title=Dick Donovan Stats|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Indians===\nWith the Indians in 1962, Donovan had better luck.<ref name=\"Bad Luck\"/> Used as the Indians' [[Opening Day]] starter, he shut out the Red Sox on April 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/BOS/BOS196204100.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Boston Red Sox Box Score, April 10, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In fact, he did not allow a run until his third game of the year, starting the season with 19 scoreless innings.<ref name=\"1962 Donovan\">{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1962|title=Dick Donovan 1962 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He commenced with an 8\u20130 start, becoming the first pitcher in the major leagues to eight wins on May 24.<ref name=\"Bad Luck\"/> Donovan was selected to the AL All-Star team in both games, allowing a run over two innings in the first one and not pitching in the second one.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Twice during the year, he hit two home runs in a game\u2014May 18 against Detroit and August 31 against Baltimore; the Indians won both instances.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=b&year=1962|title=Dick Donovan 1962 Batting Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He limited the Orioles to two hits July 2 in a 2\u20130 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196207020.shtml|title=Baltimore Orioles at Cleveland Indians Box Score, July 2, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> On August 26, he limited Boston to two hits in a 4\u20130 victory; the shutout was his third of the year against the Red Sox.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196208262.shtml|title=Boston Red Sox at Cleveland Indians Box Score, August 26, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> During a game on September 4, he limited the White Sox to two runs through 12 innings but took the loss after giving up a run in the 13th.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA196209040.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Chicago White Sox Box Score, September 4, 1962|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Donovan was rewarded for his performance in 1962, when he won 20 games for the first time in his career. In 34 starts, he had 16 complete games and five shutouts (most in the AL) in 250<small>{{fraction|1|3}}</small> innings pitched, all of them new career-highs, for Cleveland. His ERA was 3.59.<ref name=\"reference\"/> After the season, he finished fifth in MVP voting, and the ''[[Sporting News]]'' named him its AL Pitcher of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|author=United Press International|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=348&dat=19621121&id=D_YvAAAAIBAJ&pg=5262,2474618&hl=en|title=Yankees' Mickey Mantle Named 'Most Valuable'|work=The Rome News-Tribune|date=November 21, 1962|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> The Indians named him their Man of the Year and gave him a $40,000 contract for 1963.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nDespite his success in 1962, Donovan was the Indians' third starter for 1963, behind [[Mudcat Grant]] and [[Sam McDowell]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/teams/tgl.cgi?team=CLE&t=p&year=1963|title=1963 Cleveland Indians Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> On July 5, he held the Yankees to one run, had two hits, and scored a run in a 4\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CLE/CLE196307050.shtml|title=New York Yankees at Cleveland Indians Box Score, July 5, 1963|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Through August 3, he had a 6\u201310 record, but he won his next four starts by pitching four complete games in a row, including back-to-back shutouts August 8 and August 14 (when he held the White Sox scoreless for 11 innings in a 1\u20130 victory).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1963|title=Dick Donovan 1963 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 30 starts, he had an 11\u201313 record, a 4.24 ERA, three shutouts, 84 strikeouts, and 28 walks in 206 innings. For the second year in a row, he led the league in walks per nine innings, with a 1.2 mark.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nDonovan held the [[Los Angeles Angels]] to two runs over eight innings and drove in a couple of his own with a single against [[Ken McBride]] in a 3\u20132 victory over the Angels on April 23, 1964.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/LAA/LAA196404230.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Los Angeles Angels Box Score, April 23, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Through August 8, though his record was close to .500 at 6\u20137, his ERA was 4.72. After that, he was removed from the rotation. Though he made four more starts for the Indians that season, they were all in doubleheaders.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1964|title=Dick Donovan 1964 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> Against the White Sox in the second game of a doubleheader during September 6, he relinquished 16 hits but lasted into the 13th inning, when [[Pete Ward]] finally drove in a run to give Chicago a 3\u20132 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/boxes/CHA/CHA196409062.shtml|title=Cleveland Indians at Chicago White Sox Box Score, September 6, 1964|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> In 30 games (just 23 starts), he had a 7\u20139 record, a 4.55 ERA, no shutouts, 83 strikeouts, and 29 walks in {{frac|158|1|3}} innings.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\nIn 1965, Donovan was again a starter for the Indians, but only for his first two games, after which he was moved to the bullpen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=donovdi01&t=p&year=1965|title=Dick Donovan 1965 Pitching Gamelogs|work=Baseball-Reference|accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> He had not made it through the sixth inning in either of his starts, and the Indians wanted to give more starts to prospects like [[Sonny Siebert]] and [[Luis Tiant]].<ref name=\"SABR\"/> Used all but once in relief after that, he was released June 15 after posting a 5.96 ERA in 12 games.<ref name=\"reference\"/>  \u201cI figure baseball was good to me,\u201d Donovan said. \u201cI was good to a lot of people in baseball too -- the hitters. It will be nice to take it easy if I don\u2019t go with another club.\u201d<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\nDuring a 15-year major league career, Donovan compiled 122 wins, 880 strikeouts, and a 3.67 ERA, with 101 complete games, 25 shutouts and five saves. In 2,017<small>{{fraction|1|3}}</small> innings pitched, he allowed 1,988 hits and 495 walks.<ref name=\"reference\"/> \n\n==Playing style==\nDonovan threw three pitches: a [[fastball]], a [[curveball]], and a slider. He learned the slider while pitching for Atlanta, when coach and later manager Whitlow Wyatt helped teach it to him.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> In 1955, when he finally stuck in a major league team's rotation, ''Sports Illustrated'' called it \"one of the most effective pitches in baseball.\"<ref name=\"slider\"/> Among pitchers, Donovan was also an unusually gifted hitter. In 1954, he was the team MVP for Atlanta after hitting 12 home runs and driving in 38 runs in only 27 games.<ref name=\"SABR\"/> With the White Sox, he was frequently used as a pinch-hitter. At the plate in his 15-year major league career, Donovan posted a .163 batting average (113-for-694) with 67 runs, 15 home runs, 64 RBI, and 64 walks.<ref name=\"reference\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn February 7, 1959, Donovan married Patricia Casey, a [[Quincy, Massachusetts|Quincy]], Massachusetts, resident who was a stewardess for [[United Airlines]]. The couple had two children, Peter and Amy. His friend Wyatt gave him the idea to sell insurance, and Donovan had a home business selling insurance during his MLB career. In 1963, he earned his stockbroker's license and joined the Boston-based firm Eastman & Dillon. After his baseball career, he served as the executive vice president for [[Bache & Co.]]. In 1980, he opened a real estate appraisal office in Quincy, which he ran until 1994. Additionally, Donovan served as distributor with Earth Care Products, a Quincy company that makes products out of recycled plastic. He died from cancer on January 6, 1997.<ref name=\"SABR\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Major League Baseball all-time leaders in home runs by pitchers]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060502001352/http://www.baseballlibrary.com/baseballlibrary/ballplayers/D/Donovan_Dick.stm Baseball Library]\n{{baseballstats|br=d/donovdi01}}\n*{{Find a Grave}}\n\n{{AL ERA champions}}\n{{Sporting News AL Pitcher of the Year Award}}\n{{Cleveland Indians Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{Texas Rangers Opening Day starting pitchers}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Baseball}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Donovan, Dick}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:1997 deaths]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American League ERA champions]]\n[[Category:Atlanta Crackers players]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Boston Braves players]]\n[[Category:Chicago White Sox players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Detroit Tigers players]]\n[[Category:Fort Lauderdale Braves players]]\n[[Category:Evansville Braves players]]\n[[Category:Hartford Chiefs players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball pitchers]]\n[[Category:Milwaukee Brewers (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:North Quincy High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Boston]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Quincy, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Washington Senators (1961\u20131971) players]]\n\n\n{{US-baseball-pitcher-1920s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Sanfranciscogiants17", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dick_Donovan"}
